> “He who makes a beast of himself gets rid of the pain of being a man.” [^1] — Dr. Samuel Johnson, quoted in Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas by Hunter S. Thompson (1971)  

This is the beginning of a small experiment — part training log, part data science side project, part nostalgic therapy. After a long and sometimes questionable relationship with the marathon, I’ve decided to document the road to my next one — my 13th, though who's counting. I’m not chasing a personal best (at least, that’s what I tell myself), but I am chasing something: structure, understanding, maybe even redemption. This blog, and the series to follow, is a place to reflect on old performances, track new training efforts, and occasionally make sense of the numbers — or at least dress them up in tidy tables and plots that suggest control over what is an unpredictable pursuit.

The marathon doesn’t just test the man — it creates the beast in him. Not a beast of rage or reckless indulgence, like the one Hunter S. Thompson conjured in the neon haze of Vegas, but something more controlled, more methodical… yet still, undeniably, irrational. To train for a marathon is to willingly embrace a kind of madness: to rise early, log the miles, sweat through long runs, negotiate splits, and obsess over details that no one else will ever see or care about.
No different, I suppose, than compulsions of drugs or drink — except that one ends with a finisher’s medal and (hopefully) less liver damage. Still, both require full immersion. Both blur the lines between discipline and delusion. And both, in their way, are a form of chaos that allows escape from the polite constraints of ordinary life.

[^1]: Originally by Dr. Samuel Johnson, used by Hunter S. Thompson as the epigraph to *Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas* (1971).

Reflecting on my own running, I haven’t trained “properly” since 2019 — which, not coincidentally, was also my personal best (2:52). A high-water mark that I’ve stared at lovingly (and maybe delusionally) in the rear-view mirror ever since. Since then, the structure slipped. My belief systems about what "should work" in training have often charged ahead of the evidence. In hindsight, I probably need to be a better Bayesian [^4]: update my beliefs *when the data tells me to,* not just when my ego needs a pick-me-up.

[^4]: For a general introduction to Bayesian inference — the process of updating beliefs as new evidence becomes available — see the [Wikipedia article on Bayesian inference](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference).

So, why blog now?

Partly because I’m nostalgic. But also because I’ll “try” and quietly turn this into a small data science project — an excuse to tinker with my training logs, Strava uploads, physiological markers, and the occasional psychological pothole. Maybe there’s something to learn from 12 marathons. Perhaps I can pair reflection with data and write a part personal essay and part small-scale science experiment.

It’s also a chance to learn more about Quarto [^2] (the system used to create this website), and to explore how to tell a story with better visuals, interactive tables, and a cleaner presentation style. I’ve taken a liking to the Tufte handout theme [^3], and this blog gives me a good excuse to experiment with that as well. Consider it a running diary meets technical playground — one foot in the marathon world, the other in markdown.

[^2]: Quarto is an open-source scientific and technical publishing system. For documentation and source code, see the official website at [quarto.org](https://www.quarto.org) and the [GitHub repository](https://www.github.com/quarto-dev/quarto-cli).

[^3]: The Tufte theme in Quarto is inspired by Edward Tufte’s design principles, emphasizing clarity, simplicity, and effective use of white space. See the Quarto Tufte layout example at [quarto-dev.github.io](https://quarto-dev.github.io/quarto-gallery/page-layout/tufte.html).

For background, 

I'm including a table below that gives a snapshot of my past marathon performances, complete with age-graded percentages. It’s a mix of highs and “what the hell happened there?” 







